newspaper_data.title: NAACP Wages Fight on Negro Waiter Bias
newspaper_data.entry: On August 24, 1961, the Los Angeles Sentinel reported on the call from the Citizens Committee to End Discrimination against Negro Waiters for Black social, business, and religious organizations to campaign establishments that have denied permanent employment to black waiters. Three of those establishments were Frank Senne’s Ciro’s (8433 Sunset Boulevard), Frank Senne’s Moulin Rouge (6230 Sunset Boulevard), and the Beverly Hills Hotel (9641 Sunset Boulevard). This decision came after the Labor and Industry committee of the Los Angeles NAACP branch investigated and found the listed establishments had a practice of hiring Black waiters only when Black social clubs held functions.

newspaper_data.title: Desi Standup Comedy A Success – And That's No Joke
newspaper_data.entry: On May 21, 2004, India-West (the oldest Indian newspaper with the largest circulation in Western USA) reported on the success of the performances of “Intense Comedy Night” held at The Comedy Store located at 8433 Sunset Boulevard for the first time. “Intense Comedy Night,” produced by New York-based Intense Management in partnership with internet portal Desiclub.com, was a standup comedy show from second-generation Indian Americans meant to “create a platform for Indian American comics to showcase their talents and help them go mainstream.”

newspaper_data.title: Con el creador de "Pepe Tortilla" [= With the creator of "Pepe Tortilla"]
newspaper_data.entry: This article discusses stand up comedy and its prevelance in other countries and cultures, using Latin night at The Comedy Store (8433) as an example.

newspaper_data.title: Dandole sabor y color a la comedia [= Giving flavor and color to comedy]
newspaper_data.entry: Funny Ladies of Color, presented weekly at The Comedy Store (8433), is a space for women of diverse ethnicities to express themselves through comedy.
